{
  "doc_id": "41165",
  "text": "Similar to the well-established adenoma-to-carcinoma progression of colon cancer development, sporadic EC is believed to develop through a continuum from complex atypical hyperplasia (CAH) to well-differentiated cancer. Risk factors for sporadic endometrioid EC include age, obesity, nulliparity, and an excess of estrogen to progesterone ratio [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Chronic estrogen exposure is believed to trigger the transformation to hyperplasia followed by EC [CITATION_4] . However, the molecular mechanisms underlying the pathogenesis of EC remain incompletely understood. HDGF is known to play an important role in vascular growth and formation by regulating endothelial cell proliferation and migration [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Thus, HDGF derived from tumors may promote tumor growth and angiogenesis via paracrine mechanisms.",
